INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '13d893f1-170e-45a1-9af5-7d214fb8086d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$esbuild Config — Zero-Config Convenience vs Explicit Control$escape$,
  $escape$esbuild has no config file convention — there is no esbuild.config.js that it discovers automatically. Every invocation is explicit: CLI flags or a JavaScript/TypeScript build script. The "zero-config" experience comes from sane defaults (no transforms unless asked, no bundling unless --bundle is passed), not from file discovery.

For anything beyond a one-liner, a build script calling the esbuild JS API is the idiomatic pattern. You get full Node.js expressiveness: conditional logic, environment variable injection via `define`, multiple entry points, and plugin composition. The `build()` call is synchronous in intent but returns a Promise — always await it and inspect the `metafile` if you need bundle analysis.

Key config knobs developers miss: `splitting: true` requires `format: 'esm'`; `sourcemap: 'external'` writes a separate `.map` instead of inlining; `target` accepts browser version arrays like `['chrome120', 'firefox115']` — not just ES year strings. Skipping explicit `platform` defaults to `browser`, which stubs Node built-ins silently.$escape$,
  $escape$// build.ts — explicit esbuild config script
import { build } from 'esbuild';

await build({
  entryPoints: ['src/index.tsx'],
  bundle: true,
  format: 'esm',
  splitting: true,
  outdir: 'dist',
  platform: 'browser',
  target: ['chrome120', 'firefox115'],
  sourcemap: 'external',
  define: {
    'process.env.NODE_ENV': JSON.stringify(process.env.NODE_ENV ?? 'production'),
  },
  metafile: true,
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
