INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c48b1620-f122-471f-a595-24c7631eb295',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$esbuild Asset Handling — Loaders, Hashing, and Cache Busting$escape$,
  $escape$esbuild treats assets through its `loader` option — each file extension maps to a strategy. For images and fonts, `file` emits the asset to `outdir` and replaces the import with a URL string. `dataurl` inlines as a base64 data URI, useful for small icons. `base64` gives you the raw string without the URI prefix. SVGs are flexible: use `text` to import markup as a string, `dataurl` to embed inline, or `file` to emit and reference externally.

Cache busting is handled via `assetNames`. The `[hash]` placeholder generates a content hash from the file bytes — deterministic and stable across rebuilds unless the file changes. Pair it with `[dir]/[name]-[hash]` to preserve directory structure. Set `publicPath` to prefix emitted URLs with your CDN origin, so `import logo from './logo.png'` resolves to `https://cdn.example.com/assets/logo-Xk92a.png` at runtime.

For SVG sprite workflows, import SVGs as `text`, concatenate symbols server-side, and emit once — esbuild won't deduplicate identical `file`-loaded assets automatically, so manual bundling still wins there.$escape$,
  $escape$import * as esbuild from 'esbuild';

await esbuild.build({
  entryPoints: ['src/index.ts'],
  bundle: true,
  outdir: 'dist',
  publicPath: 'https://cdn.example.com/',
  assetNames: 'assets/[name]-[hash]',
  loader: {
    '.png':  'file',
    '.jpg':  'file',
    '.svg':  'dataurl',
    '.woff2': 'file',
    '.ttf':  'base64',
  },
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
