INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7def1216-6825-4b33-9cac-879c583d8db1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$esbuild Source Maps — Types, Trade-offs, and What to Ship to Production$escape$,
  $escape$esbuild supports four source map modes via the `sourcemap` option: `true` (or `"linked"`), `"external"`, `"inline"`, and `"both"`. Each has distinct production implications.

`"linked"` emits a separate `.js.map` file and appends a `//# sourceMappingURL=` comment to the bundle — best for production when you serve maps privately or upload to Sentry/Datadog. `"external"` does the same but omits the URL comment, giving you the file without exposing the reference to end users. `"inline"` base64-encodes the entire map into the bundle — never use this in production; it inflates bundle size by 2–3×. `"both"` combines inline and external, useful only for tooling compatibility.

For esbuild specifically, source maps are generated at near-zero cost due to its columnar AST design — unlike webpack, there's no measurable build-time penalty for enabling them. The real trade-off is exposure: shipping `"linked"` maps publicly leaks your source tree. Use `"external"`, strip the `sourceMappingURL` comment at deploy time, then upload the `.map` files directly to your error tracker using its CLI before deleting them from the artifact.$escape$,
  $escape$import * as esbuild from 'esbuild';

await esbuild.build({
  entryPoints: ['src/index.ts'],
  bundle: true,
  minify: true,
  outdir: 'dist',
  // Emit .map files without linking them in the bundle output
  sourcemap: 'external',
});

// Post-build: upload to Sentry, then delete
// npx @sentry/cli sourcemaps upload --org=acme --project=web dist/
// rm dist/*.map$escape$,
  $escape$javascript$escape$,
